\begin{align*}
\|T x\|^2 &= \sum_{i=1}^m (Ax)^2_i = \sum_{i=1}^m \left(\sum_{j=1}^n a_{ij}x_j\right)^2 \\
&\stackrel{C.S.}{\leq} \sum_{i=1}^m \left(\sum_{j=1}^n a^2_{ij}\right) \cdot \left(\sum_{j=1}^n x^2_j\right) \\
&= \|A\|^2\|x\|^2
\end{align*}

Therefore, $\|T x\| \leq \|A\|\|x\|$ for all $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$, which implies $\|T\| \leq \|A\|$.

statement:
\begin{itemize}
\item $C(K)$ is separable for any compact set $K \subset \mathbb{R}^n$.
\item The sequence space $\ell^p(F)$, $F = \mathbb{R}$ or $F = \mathbb{C}$, is separable for $1 \leq p < \infty$.
\item The function spaces $L^p(K)$ is separable for any compact subset $K \subset \mathbb{R}^n$ and any $1 \leq p < \infty$.
\end{itemize}
We remark that more generally $L^p(\Omega)$ is separable for arbitrary (measurable) domains $\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^n$ and $1 \leq p < \infty$.

proof:
\begin{proof}
(i) Suppose first that $\operatorname{span}(S)$ is dense. Then for any $f \in S^\circ$, we have by linearity that also $f|_Y = 0$ where we set $Y = \operatorname{span}(S)$. As $Y$ is dense in $X$ we thus get that $f = 0$ by Lemma 4.1.4.

Conversely, suppose that $\operatorname{span}(S)$ is not dense. Then $Y = \operatorname{span}(S)$ is a closed proper subspace of $X$ so we can choose $x_0 \in X \setminus Y$ and apply Proposition 6.4.2 to obtain an $f \in X^*$ with $f|_Y = 0$ and $f(x_0) = \|x_0\| \neq 0$ so have found an element $f \neq 0$ of $S^\circ$.

(ii) Suppose that there exists $x \in T^\circ$ with $x \neq 0$. Then by Corollary 6.3.3 there exists $f \in X^*$ so that $f(x) \neq f(0) = 0$. If $\operatorname{span}(T)$ is dense in $X^*$ we can however find a sequence $(f_n)$ of elements of $\operatorname{span}(T)$ that converges $f_n \to f$ in the sense of $X^*$. Note that since $x \in T^\circ$ we have that $f_n(x) = 0$ which leads to a contradiction as $0 \neq f(x) = \lim_{n\to\infty} f_n(x)$.
\end{proof}
